</svg><span class=3D"astro-kxnmhzey">SAML SSO</span> </p> <div class=3D"con=
tent astro-kxnmhzey"> <p>If your team requires you to log in with <a href=
=3D"https://docs.netlify.com/manage/security/secure-netlify-access/configur=
e-team-saml-sso">single sign-on (SSO)</a>, your personal access tokens will=
 be denied access to the team by default. You can choose to grant access to=
 the team when you generate a new token. You must be logged in to the team =
with SSO to grant access to it.</p> </div> </aside>
<p>If you=E2=80=99re making a public integration with Netlify for others to=
 enjoy, you must use OAuth2. This allows users to authorize your applicatio=
n to use Netlify on their behalf without having to copy/paste API tokens or=
 touch sensitive login info. You=E2=80=99ll need an application client key =
and a client secret to integrate with the Netlify API. You can register a n=
ew application in your Netlify user settings for <a href=3D"https://app.net=
lify.com/applications" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" =
target=3D"_blank">OAuth applications</a>. Visit our blog post on <a href=3D=
"https://www.netlify.com/blog/2016/10/10/integrating-with-netlify-oauth2/" =
class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank">integ=
rating with Netlify</a> for more information including common grant types a=
nd an example project.</p>
<p>The OAuth2 end-user authorization endpoint is <code dir=3D"auto">https:/=
/app.netlify.com/authorize</code>.</p>
