e>
<p>Use <code dir=3D"auto">Content-Type: application/octet-stream</code> and=
 use the file contents as the HTTP request body.</p>
<p>If the required file is a function, upload it to the functions endpoint,=
 again using the deploy ID returned as <code dir=3D"auto">id</code> in the =
file digest response:</p>
<div class=3D"expressive-code"><figure class=3D"frame not-content"><figcapt=
ion class=3D"header"></figcaption><pre data-language=3D"plaintext"><code><d=
iv class=3D"ec-line"><div class=3D"code"><span style=3D"--0:#a6accd">PUT /a=
pi/v1/deploys/{deploy_id}/functions/hello-world?runtime=3Djs</span></div></=
div></code></pre><div class=3D"copy"><div aria-live=3D"polite"></div><butto=
n title=3D"Copy to clipboard" data-copied=3D"Copied!" data-code=3D"PUT /api=
/v1/deploys/{deploy_id}/functions/hello-world?runtime=3Djs"><div></div></bu=
tton></div></figure></div>
<p>Possible <code dir=3D"auto">runtime</code> parameters are:</p>
<ul>
<li><code dir=3D"auto">js</code>: zipped Node.js programs or bundled JavaSc=
ript files</li>
<li><code dir=3D"auto">go</code>: Go binaries</li>
</ul>
<p>When uploading functions, use the name of the function, not the file pat=
h or any file extensions. Clients must zip the function prior to uploading =
to the API.</p>
<p>Once all files have been uploaded, Netlify will post process the deploy =
and invalidate the CDN.</p>
